				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha =0.05$$\end{document}α=0.05), were listed in Supplementary Tables S2 to S4.

A hierarchical clustering algorithm was applied to the extracted PCs (HCPC) to detect inner structures in the data and to provide a phenotypic classification of the Italian rice varietal landscape. Only the first three PCs were used in the analysis to reduce noise. Three clusters were selected to maximise the relative loss of inertia30. We provide the complete list of varieties in each cluster in Supplementary Table S5; data plotted in PCs space colour-coded by cluster is presented in Fig. 4. The obtained partition was compared to the original qualitative and quantitative variables, using an alpha level \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
