Half of the genotypes in Cluster C had ‘long A (IC)’ grain shape (v = 5.8, p < 0.001), while ‘long B’ genotypes were absent. The 75% of genotypes bred in G1 (v = 5.4, p < 0.001) and G2 (v = 5.4, p < 0.001), and 48.4% of the varieties in G3 (v = 3.95, p < 0.001) were included in this cluster, implying that roughly 80% of these genotypes were bred before 1990. Phylogenetic subgroups ‘IIe’ (v = 5.38, p < 0.001) and ‘IIf’ (v = 5.14, p < 0.001) strongly characterised Cluster C, which comprised 52.56% and 55.74%, of the varieties in these two subgroups, respectively. Since Cluster C included many genotypes from pre-mechanisation periods, it had the highest mean for traits ‘stem length’ (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
